<h2>Hands-on case: detecting a suspicious docker exec</h2>

<p>The most security-relevant event is when someone runs an interactive shell inside a container. Simulate it like this:</p>

<pre><code># Spin up a test container
docker run -d --name test_nginx nginx:latest

# Run an interactive shell (this is what we want to detect)
docker exec -it test_nginx /bin/sh</code></pre>

<p>Wazuh captures two events: <code>exec_create</code> and <code>exec_start</code>. The second triggers rule 87907 at level 5. To raise it to level 12 and map it to MITRE ATT&CK T1609, add this custom rule to the <strong>manager's</strong> <code>/var/ossec/etc/rules/local_rules.xml</code>:</p>

<pre><code>&lt;group name="docker,shell_access"&gt;
  &lt;rule id="100110" level="12"&gt;
    &lt;if_sid&gt;87907&lt;/if_sid&gt;
    &lt;field name="docker.Action"&gt;exec_start: (/bin/sh|/bin/bash|/bin/zsh|sh|bash)&lt;/field&gt;
    &lt;description&gt;Docker: Interactive shell launched in container $(docker.Actor.Attributes.name)&lt;/description&gt;
    &lt;options&gt;no_full_log&lt;/options&gt;
    &lt;group&gt;docker_shell,attack,T1609&lt;/group&gt;
  &lt;/rule&gt;

  &lt;!-- Privileged container: risk of escaping to the host --&gt;
  &lt;rule id="100111" level="14"&gt;
    &lt;if_sid&gt;87901&lt;/if_sid&gt;
    &lt;field name="docker.Actor.Attributes.privileged"&gt;true&lt;/field&gt;
    &lt;description&gt;Docker: Privileged container created - $(docker.Actor.Attributes.name)&lt;/description&gt;
    &lt;group&gt;docker_privileged,pci_dss_10.6.1&lt;/group&gt;
  &lt;/rule&gt;
&lt;/group&gt;</code></pre>

<p>Apply the changes on the manager:</p>

<pre><code>sudo /var/ossec/bin/wazuh-logtest    # verify the rule has no errors
sudo systemctl restart wazuh-manager</code></pre>

<h2>Extra: SCA Docker CIS Benchmark</h2>

<p>Wazuh doesn't include the Docker CIS policy by default in its standard installation (unlike the policies for Ubuntu or RHEL), but you can add it manually. The official Wazuh blog publishes a YAML file with the 98 controls of the CIS Docker Benchmark v1.7.0.</p>

<p>Once you have the <code>cis_docker_bench.yml</code> file, enable it in the agent's <code>ossec.conf</code>:</p>

<pre><code>&lt;sca&gt;
  &lt;enabled&gt;yes&lt;/enabled&gt;
  &lt;scan_on_start&gt;yes&lt;/scan_on_start&gt;
  &lt;interval&gt;12h&lt;/interval&gt;
  &lt;skip_nfs&gt;yes&lt;/skip_nfs&gt;
  &lt;policies&gt;
    &lt;policy&gt;/var/ossec/etc/sca/cis_docker_bench.yml&lt;/policy&gt;
  &lt;/policies&gt;
&lt;/sca&gt;</code></pre>

<p>This will check things like: whether containers run as root, whether the rootfs is read-only, whether sensitive host volumes are mounted, or whether the Docker socket is exposed inside any container.</p>

<h2>Extra: Scanning image vulnerabilities with Trivy</h2>

<p>Wazuh's <code>vulnerability-detection</code> module analyzes the agent's OS packages, but not the internal layers of the Docker images. For that it integrates with <a href="https://trivy.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Trivy</a>:</p>

<pre><code># Install Trivy on the host
wget -qO - https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb/public.key | \
  gpg --dearmor | sudo tee /usr/share/keyrings/trivy.gpg &gt; /dev/null
echo "deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/trivy.gpg] \
  https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb generic main" | \
  sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/trivy.list
sudo apt-get update &amp;&amp; sudo apt-get install trivy

# Scan an image manually
trivy image nginx:latest</code></pre>

<p>You can then use the <code>command</code> wodle to run Trivy periodically and send the results to Wazuh as events, where custom rules will turn them into level 7 (HIGH) or 12 (CRITICAL) alerts.</p>

<h2>Full agent configuration</h2>

<p>A summary of all the blocks you add to the Docker host's <code>/var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf</code>:</p>

<pre><code>&lt;!-- 1. Docker Listener --&gt;
&lt;wodle name="docker-listener"&gt;
  &lt;interval&gt;10m&lt;/interval&gt;
  &lt;attempts&gt;5&lt;/attempts&gt;
  &lt;run_on_start&gt;yes&lt;/run_on_start&gt;
  &lt;disabled&gt;no&lt;/disabled&gt;
&lt;/wodle&gt;

&lt;!-- 2. Container logs --&gt;
&lt;localfile&gt;
  &lt;log_format&gt;syslog&lt;/log_format&gt;
  &lt;location&gt;/var/lib/docker/containers/*/*-json.log&lt;/location&gt;
&lt;/localfile&gt;

&lt;!-- 3. FIM --&gt;
&lt;syscheck&gt;
  &lt;directories realtime="yes" check_all="yes" report_changes="yes"&gt;/etc/docker&lt;/directories&gt;
  &lt;directories realtime="yes" check_all="yes"&gt;/run/docker.sock&lt;/directories&gt;
  &lt;directories check_all="yes"&gt;/usr/bin/docker&lt;/directories&gt;
  &lt;ignore&gt;/var/lib/docker/overlay2&lt;/ignore&gt;
  &lt;ignore&gt;/var/lib/docker/containers&lt;/ignore&gt;
  &lt;ignore&gt;/var/lib/docker/tmp&lt;/ignore&gt;
&lt;/syscheck&gt;</code></pre>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>What can Wazuh monitor on a Docker server?</h3>
<p>Installing the Wazuh agent on the Linux host gives you four layers of visibility without any agent inside the containers: Docker API events (start, stop, exec, image pulls) through the <code>docker-listener</code> module, container logs collected from the host filesystem, file integrity (FIM) over the Docker configuration, and image vulnerabilities through integration with Trivy or Grype.</p>

<h3>Do you need to install a Wazuh agent inside each container?</h3>
<p>No. A single Wazuh agent on the Docker host monitors the daemon and every container running on it. The <code>docker-listener</code> module talks to the Docker API, container logs are read from <code>/var/lib/docker/containers</code> on the host, and FIM watches the Docker configuration. You never install anything inside the containers themselves.</p>

<h3>Why use log_format syslog instead of json for Docker container logs?</h3>
<p>Even though Docker's <code>json-file</code> driver writes JSON, you should use <code>log_format syslog</code> so Wazuh reads each full line and lets its decoders extract the fields. If you set <code>log_format json</code>, the parser tries to interpret Docker's wrapper (the <code>log</code>, <code>stream</code>, and <code>time</code> fields) and can break on the actual log content inside.</p>

<h3>How do you detect a suspicious interactive shell in a container with Wazuh?</h3>
<p>When someone runs <code>docker exec</code> to open a shell, Wazuh captures <code>exec_create</code> and <code>exec_start</code> events; the latter triggers rule 87907 at level 5. You can add a custom rule (id 100110) on the manager that raises it to level 12 and maps it to MITRE ATT&CK T1609, matching shells like <code>/bin/sh</code> or <code>/bin/bash</code>, so an interactive access generates a high-severity alert.</p>

<h3>Should FIM monitor the whole /var/lib/docker directory?</h3>
<p>No. You should monitor Docker's configuration files like <code>/etc/docker</code>, the socket, and the binaries, but explicitly ignore <code>/var/lib/docker/overlay2</code>, <code>/var/lib/docker/containers</code>, and <code>/var/lib/docker/tmp</code>. Those data directories can grow to hundreds of GB and change constantly with overlay2 layers, which would generate thousands of false FIM alerts.</p>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

<p>With this configuration you have full visibility over your Docker server: real-time API events, centralized logs from all containers, alerts on any change to the daemon configuration, and immediate detection of suspicious interactive access. All without any agent inside the containers.</p>

<p>If you also add Trivy and the SCA Docker CIS policy, you cover image vulnerabilities and misconfigurations too, before they reach production.</p>

